import AboutHeroImage from '../assets/blog-placeholder-about.jpg';
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Sunil Mayya — software engineer at Mozilla, father of two, and enthusiastic home cook, based in Nuremberg."
	pubDate={new Date('June 28 2026')}
	heroImage={AboutHeroImage}
>
	<p>
		Hi, I'm Sunil Mayya. I'm a software engineer at Mozilla working on Firefox —
		primarily the web platform and networking. Day to day that means implementing
		web-platform features in Gecko and taking part in the standards conversations
		(WICG, IETF, W3C) that shape them.
	</p>

	<p>
		A lot of my recent work sits at the boundary between the browser and the
		network:
		<a href="https://wicg.github.io/local-network-access/">Local Network Access</a>,
		<a href="https://wicg.github.io/nav-speculation/speculation-rules.html">Speculation Rules</a>,
		HTTP <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Headers/No-Vary-Search">No-Vary-Search</a>,
		the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API">Fetch API</a>
		(including <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/RequestInit#keepalive">keepalive</a>),
		and <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WebTransport">WebTransport</a>.
		What I enjoy most are the parts of the job that never make it into the release
		notes — the design tradeoffs, the cross-vendor disagreements, and the small
		implementation details you only really understand once you try to ship the
		thing. This site is where I write those down: browser internals and web
		standards explained from the inside, for the version of me who could have used
		the explanation a few years ago.
	</p>

	<p>
		I'm based in <strong>Nuremberg, Germany</strong> — a city I've grown to love
		for its balance of old-town charm and quiet, walkable everyday life. Working
		on a browser used by hundreds of millions of people from a desk here still
		feels like a small marvel of the open web.
	</p>

	<p>
		Away from the keyboard, my most important title is <strong>father of two</strong>.
		My kids are a daily reminder that the most interesting problems aren't always
		the technical ones, and that patience is a skill you can keep practicing for
		the rest of your life. A good chunk of the "life in general" writing here will
		probably trace back to them in one way or another.
	</p>

	<p>
		I also <strong>love to cook</strong>. The kitchen is where I unwind — there's
		something deeply satisfying about following a process end to end and getting
		to eat the result, which is more than I can say for most bugs. I'll be sharing
		recipes here: the ones I keep coming back to, the experiments that worked, and
		occasionally the ones that didn't.
	</p>

	<p>
		So this site is a bit of a mix — browser engineering, recipes, and notes on
		life. If any of that resonates, I'd love to hear from you. You can reach me at
		<a href="mailto:smayya@mozilla.com">smayya@mozilla.com</a>, and you'll find a
		lot of my work in the open on
		<a href="https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/">Bugzilla</a> and across Mozilla's
		<a href="https://github.com/mozilla">GitHub</a>.
	</p>

	<p>
		<em>The opinions on this site are my own and don't necessarily represent
		those of Mozilla.</em>
	</p>
</Layout>
